<p>The genre originated in the 1968 American horror film <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Night_of_the_Living_Dead" title=3D"Night of the L=
iving Dead">Night of the Living Dead</a></i>, which was directed by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_A._Romero" title=3D"George A. Rome=
ro">George A. Romero</a>, who took inspiration from the 1954 novel <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Am_Legend_(novel)" title=3D"I Am Lege=
nd (novel)">I Am Legend</a></i> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Richard_Matheson" title=3D"Richard Matheson">Richard Matheson</a>. Romero'=
s film introduced the concept of the flesh-eating zombie and spawned numero=
us other fictional works, including films, video games, and literature.
</p><p>The zombie apocalypse has been used as a metaphor for various contem=
porary fears, such as global contagion, the breakdown of society, and the e=
nd of the world. It has repeatedly been referenced in the media and has ins=
pired various fan activities such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Zombie_walk" title=3D"Zombie walk">zombie walks</a>, making zombie apoca=
lypse a dominant genre in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Popular_=
culture" title=3D"Popular culture">popular culture</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Origins">Origins</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZombie_apocalypse&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Origins"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The myth of the zombie originated in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Haiti" title=3D"Haiti">Haiti</a> in the 17th and 18th centuries when =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African_slaves" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"African slaves">African slaves</a> were brought in to work on =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sugar_plantations" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Sugar plantations">sugar plantations</a> under the rule of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/France" title=3D"France">France</a=
>. The slaves believed that if they ended their own lives by suicide they w=
ould be condemned to spend eternity trapped in their own bodies as the unde=
ad. This myth evolved in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haiti=
an_Vodou" title=3D"Haitian Vodou">Voodoo religion</a> into the Haitian beli=
ef that corpses were reanimated by shamans.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_1-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#=
cite_note-:4-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> The zombie concept eventually infiltrated wester=
n culture with the publication of the first example of zombie fiction in 19=
27, which was a book titled <i>The Magic Island</i> written by <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Seabrook" title=3D"William Seabrook">W=
illiam Seabrook</a>. The book was later adapted for cinema as the 1932 film=
 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_Zombie_(film)" title=3D"=
White Zombie (film)">White Zombie</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_n=
ote-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Directed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vict=
or_Halperin" title=3D"Victor Halperin">Victor Halperin</a> and starring <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bela_Lugosi" title=3D"Bela Lugosi">Be=
la Lugosi</a>, it was the first feature-length zombie film, establishing th=
e sub genre of zombies and paving the way for the zombie apocalypse in cine=
ma.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:5_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-:5-3"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>An early inspirational work of the genre was <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Matheson" title=3D"Richard Matheson">Richard Math=
eson</a>'s novel <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Am_Legend_(n=
ovel)" title=3D"I Am Legend (novel)">I Am Legend</a></i> (1954), which feat=
ures a lone survivor named Robert Neville waging a war against a human popu=
lation transformed into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vampires" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vampires">vampires</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-C=
lasen_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zom=
bie_apocalypse#cite_note-Clasen-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The novel has been adapted in=
to several screenplays, including <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/The_Last_Man_on_Earth_(1964_film)" title=3D"The Last Man on Earth (1964 =
film)">The Last Man on Earth</a></i> (1964), starring <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vincent_Price" title=3D"Vincent Price">Vincent Price</a=
>, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Omega_Man" title=3D"The =
Omega Man">The Omega Man</a></i> (1971), starring <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Charlton_Heston" title=3D"Charlton Heston">Charlton Heston<=
/a> and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Am_Legend_(film)" tit=
le=3D"I Am Legend (film)">I Am Legend</a></i> (2007) starring <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Will_Smith" title=3D"Will Smith">Will Smith</a>=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/George_A._Romero" title=3D"George A. Romero">George A. Ro=
mero</a> took inspiration from Matheson and developed the idea with his apo=
calyptic feature <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Night_of_the_L=
iving_Dead" title=3D"Night of the Living Dead">Night of the Living Dead</a>=
</i> (1968), but for vampires he substituted shuffling <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghoul" title=3D"Ghoul">ghouls</a>. Romero stated, "I c=
onfessed to him that I basically ripped the idea off from <i>I Am Legend</i=
>. He forgave me because we didn't make any money. He said, 'Well, as long =
as you didn't get rich, it's okay.'"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-6"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> Romero said that he never referred to the monsters in his film =
as "zombies". Instead, the term appeared in an article in <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cahiers_du_Cin%C3%A9ma" title=3D"Cahiers du Cin=
=C3=A9ma">Cahiers du Cin=C3=A9ma</a></i>. Romero commented that earlier dep=
ictions of zombies in film, "were very Caribbean and it was all to do with =
voodoo". By contrast his versions were flesh-eating monsters returned from =
the grave: "We thought up very few rules or powers for them. The idea was t=
hey are your neighbours in a different state. One of the few early ideas we=
 did have was that you have to shoot them in the head to kill them".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-:3_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-:3-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Story_elements">Story eleme=
nts</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZombie_a=
pocalypse&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Story e=
lements"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Zombies_NightoftheLivingDead.=
jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org=
/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Zombies_NightoftheLivingDead.jpg/250px-Zombie=
s_NightoftheLivingDead.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"180"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2048" data-file-height=3D"147=
2"></a><figcaption><i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Night_of_the=
_Living_Dead" title=3D"Night of the Living Dead">Night of the Living Dead</=
a></i> established most of the tropes associated with the genre, including =
unintelligent but relentless zombies.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Engine_8-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#c=
ite_note-Engine-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>Several themes and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trope_(cinem=
a)" title=3D"Trope (cinema)">tropes</a> commonly appear in zombie-apocalyps=
e films:
</p>
<ul><li>Initial contacts with zombies are extremely traumatic, causing shoc=
k, panic, disbelief, and possibly denial, hampering survivors' ability to d=
eal with hostile encounters.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-=
Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span =
title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2022)">c=
itation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></li>
<li>Official responses to the threat are slower than its rate of growth, gi=
ving the zombie plague time to expand beyond containment. This results in t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collapse_of_society" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Collapse of society">collapse of society</a>. Zombies =
take full control while small groups of the living must fight for their sur=
vival.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-:1-9"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The plot usually follows a single group of survivors caught up in the s=
udden rush of the crisis. The narrative generally focuses on the characters=
' attempts to survive on their own, concentrating on their reactions to the=
 catastrophe and the group's consequent safety.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#=
cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Generally, films have depicted zombies as the slow, lumbering, and unint=
elligent kind first popularized in the 1968 film <i>Night of the Living Dea=
d</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Engine_8-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-Engine-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
Zombies were repeatedly shown in slow-walking groups demonstrating <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herd_behavior" title=3D"Herd behavior">he=
rd behavior</a> and overwhelming victims by strength of numbers. In the 200=
0s, several films featured zombies that are depicted as more agile, vicious=
, intelligent, and stronger than the traditional zombie. In many cases of t=
hese "fast" zombies, e.g., <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/28_D=
ays_Later" title=3D"28 Days Later">28 Days Later</a></i>, <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombieland" title=3D"Zombieland">Zombieland</a><=
/i>, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dying_Light" title=3D"Dyin=
g Light">Dying Light</a></i>, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
he_Last_of_Us_(video_game)" title=3D"The Last of Us (video game)">The Last =
of Us</a></i>, and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Left_4_Dead"=
 title=3D"Left 4 Dead">Left 4 Dead</a></i>, the plot involves not re-animat=
ed corpses but living humans infected with a pathogen. Improved <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer-generated_imagery" title=3D"Computer=
-generated imagery">CGI</a> technology and the rise of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/First-person_shooter" title=3D"First-person shooter">f=
irst-person shooter</a> video games resulted in the herd behavior being rep=
laced by zombies capable of running, jumping, and attacking as individuals.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Thematic_subtext">Thematic =
subtext</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZomb=
ie_apocalypse&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: The=
matic subtext"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>From the beginnings of the genre, film makers have used the zombie apoca=
lypse as a metaphor for various cultural fears and social tensions, includi=
ng the spread of disease and plague.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-1=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> The narrative of a zombie apocalypse carries strong connecti=
ons to the turbulent social landscape of the United States in the 1960s whe=
n the originator of this genre, the film <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Night_of_the_Living_Dead" title=3D"Night of the Living Dead">Nigh=
t of the Living Dead</a></i>, was created.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4dead_13-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalyp=
se#cite_note-4dead-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rockoff_14-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#c=
ite_note-Rockoff-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-15"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>=20
</p><p>At the time when Romero was shooting the film, Americans were viewin=
g televised images of various violent events, including the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1967_Newark_riots" title=3D"1967 Newark riots">19=
67 Newark riots</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1967_Detroit_=
riot" title=3D"1967 Detroit riot">1967 Detroit riot</a> and the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vietnam_War" title=3D"Vietnam War">Vietnam Wa=
r</a>. Erin C. Cassese, associate professor of political science, commented=
 that public fears over racial tensions are reflected in the faces of the z=
ombie horde in the film and that the dehumanisation of the zombie is a warn=
ing about human psychology.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-16"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> This commentary on the civil war between races was however accidental=
. Romero had hired African-American actor <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Duane_Jones" title=3D"Duane Jones">Duane Jones</a> simply because h=
e was the best actor, but noted that after finishing the film, "that very n=
ight we heard the news that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin=
_Luther_King_Jr." title=3D"Martin Luther King Jr.">Martin Luther King</a> h=
ad been shot. There were race riots everywhere".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_7-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocal=
ypse#cite_note-:3-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Christopher Shaw writing for <i><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Guardian" title=3D"The Guardian">The Guar=
dian</a></i> noted that Romero's 1978 follow-up film <i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dawn_of_the_Dead_(1978_film)" title=3D"Dawn of the De=
ad (1978 film)">Dawn of the Dead</a></i> is a satire on <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consumer_society" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cons=
umer society">consumer society</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-17=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> In the film, zombies overrun a shopping mall where survivors =
have taken refuge. Javier Zarracina for <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Vox_Media" title=3D"Vox Media">Vox</a></i> commented, "The zombies=
 in <i>Dawn of the Dead</i> underscore the fears of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Capitalism" title=3D"Capitalism">capitalism</a> and mindl=
ess consumption that racked the late 1970s". From the 1980s, the zombie apo=
calypse was driven by a fear of global contagion, due to the appearance of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ebola" title=3D"Ebola">Ebola</a> i=
n 1976, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HIV/AIDS" title=3D"HIV/AID=
S">AIDS</a> in 1980, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avian_Flu" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Avian Flu">Avian Flu</a> in the mid-90s and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SARS" title=3D"SARS">SARS</a> in 200=
3.=20
</p><p>This fear of contagion provided creators with a new explanation for =
the zombie apocalypse. The contagion concept was used in the 1996 video gam=
e <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resident_Evil_(1996_video_gam=
e)" title=3D"Resident Evil (1996 video game)">Resident Evil</a></i> and the=
 2002 film <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/28_Days_Later" title=
=3D"28 Days Later">28 Days Later</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_18-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#c=
ite_note-:0-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> From the beginning of the post-apocalyptic tele=
vision series <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Walking_Dead_=
(TV_series)" title=3D"The Walking Dead (TV series)">The Walking Dead</a></i=
> in 2010, the predominant theme shifted from a fear of the zombie horde to=
 the fear of other humans. The series focuses on small groups of survivors =
driven by self-preservation and protected by walls designed to keep out bot=
h the zombies and other survivors.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_18-1" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_not=
e-:0-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max_Brooks" t=
itle=3D"Max Brooks">Max Brooks</a> opined that the zombie genre allows peop=
le to deal with their own anxiety about the end of the world.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zomb=
ie_apocalypse#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He commented, "People have a lot of=
 anxiety about the future. They're constantly being battered with these ver=
y scary, very global catastrophes. I think a lot of people think the system=
 is breaking down and just like the 1970s, people need a 'safe place' to ex=
plore their apocalyptic worries".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_9-1" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-=
:1-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Paffenroth" t=
itle=3D"Kim Paffenroth">Kim Paffenroth</a> noted that "more than any other =
monster, zombies are fully and literally apocalyptic... they signal the end=
 of the world as we have known it."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Paffenroth_20-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse=
#cite_note-Paffenroth-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Reception">Reception</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZombie_apocalypse&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Reception"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Initial public reaction to the zombie apocalypse genre was immediately p=
ositive. When <i>Night of the Living Dead</i> premiered at the Fulton Theat=
er in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pittsburgh" title=3D"Pittsbu=
rgh">Pittsburgh</a> on October 1, 1968, the film was an instant hit and was=
 well received by movie goers in America and Europe. It received praise fro=
m <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sight_%26_Sound" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Sight &amp; Sound">Sight and Sound</a></i> magazine in B=
ritain and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cahiers_du_Cin%C3%A9=
ma" title=3D"Cahiers du Cin=C3=A9ma">Cahiers du Cin=C3=A9ma</a></i> in Fran=
ce. By contrast, critical reception was mainly negative. A reviewer for <i>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variety_(magazine)" title=3D"Varie=
ty (magazine)">Variety</a></i> commented that the film raised, "doubts abou=
t the future of the regional cinema movement and the moral health of filmgo=
ers who cheerfully opt for unrelieved sadism."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:6_21-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocaly=
pse#cite_note-:6-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The graphic violence depicted in the film =
caused particular controversy. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pau=
line_Kael" title=3D"Pauline Kael">Pauline Kael</a> writing for <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_Yorker" title=3D"The New Yorker">=
The New Yorker</a></i> described it as, "one of the most gruesomely terrify=
ing movies ever made".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-22"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Ebert" title=3D"Roger Ebe=
rt">Roger Ebert</a> wrote a review of the film for the <i><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_Sun-Times" title=3D"Chicago Sun-Times">Chic=
ago Sun-Times</a></i>, in which he commented on the reaction of the young a=
udience: "I don't think the younger kids really knew what hit them. They'd =
seen horror movies before, but this was something else. This was ghouls eat=
ing people=E2=80=94you could actually see what they were eating. This was l=
ittle girls killing their mothers. This was being set on fire. Worst of all=
, nobody got out alive=E2=80=94even the hero got killed". The film has sinc=
e been recognised as a classic by film critics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:6_21-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocal=
ypse#cite_note-:6-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In October 2018, Steve Rose writing for <=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Guardian" title=3D"The Guard=
ian">The Guardian</a></i> described it as, "brilliantly perplexing, horrify=
ing and mysteriously allegorical".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-23"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> Several decades after the release of <i>Night of the Living De=
ad</i>, the popularity of the genre has only increased. Films like <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/28_Days_Later" title=3D"28 Days Later">=
28 Days Later</a></i>, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dawn_of_=
the_Dead_(2004_film)" title=3D"Dawn of the Dead (2004 film)">Dawn of the De=
ad</a></i>, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaun_of_the_Dead" =
title=3D"Shaun of the Dead">Shaun of the Dead</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombieland" title=3D"Zombieland">Zombieland</a><=
/i>, as well as video games in the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Resident_Evil" title=3D"Resident Evil">Resident Evil</a></i> series and=
 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Last_of_Us_(video_game)" t=
itle=3D"The Last of Us (video game)">The Last of Us</a></i> have been major=
 commercial successes. In 2010, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fr=
ank_Darabont" title=3D"Frank Darabont">Frank Darabont</a>, executive produc=
er of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Walking_Dead_(TV_seri=
es)" title=3D"The Walking Dead (TV series)">The Walking Dead</a></i> commen=
ted, "To be a fan of zombie films was a really sub-cult thing for many deca=
des. In the last five years, it's become massively mainstream".<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-:6_21-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-:6-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Genre_controversy">Genre co=
ntroversy</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZo=
mbie_apocalypse&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: G=
enre controversy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>The release of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/28_Days_Later=
" title=3D"28 Days Later">28 Days Later</a></i> in 2002 created a long-runn=
ing debate over whether the film could be categorised within the genre of z=
ombie apocalypse. This was based on the technicality that the people infect=
ed with rage in the film are still alive rather than returning from the gra=
ve. The debate was further fuelled by the director <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Danny_Boyle" title=3D"Danny Boyle">Danny Boyle</a> choosin=
g not to label the film as a zombie movie. Screenwriter <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alex_Garland" title=3D"Alex Garland">Alex Garland</a>=
 finally settled the matter by stating, "Whatever technical discrepancies m=
ay or may not exist, they're pretty much zombies".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalyp=
se#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_other_media">In other me=
dia</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZombie_a=
pocalypse&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: In othe=
r media"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Academic_research">Academic=
 research</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZo=
mbie_apocalypse&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: A=
cademic research"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<div style=3D"float: right; width: 39%;"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote=
 rquote"><p>While aggressive quarantine may contain the epidemic, or a cure=
 may lead to coexistence of humans and zombies, the most effective way to c=
ontain the rise of the undead is to hit hard and hit often.</p></blockquote=
><div class=3D"templatequotecite"><p style=3D"display: inline; padding-left=
: 2.3em;">=E2=80=94=E2=80=8APhilip Munz, Ioan Hudea, Joe Imad, and Robert J=
. Smith? [sic], "When Zombies Attack!" (2009)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-WhenZombie=
s_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie=
_apocalypse#cite_note-WhenZombies-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><span style=3D"display:non=
e" data-plural=3D"0"></span></p></div></div>
<p>According to a 2009 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carleton_Un=
iversity" title=3D"Carleton University">Carleton University</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Ottawa" title=3D"University=
 of Ottawa">University of Ottawa</a> epidemiological analysis, an outbreak =
of slow zombies "is likely to lead to the collapse of civilization, unless =
it is dealt with quickly." Based on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Mathematical_model" title=3D"Mathematical model">mathematical modelling</=
a>, the authors concluded that offensive strategies were the most reliable,=
 due to risks that can compromise a quarantine. They also found that a cure=
 would leave few humans alive, since this would do little to slow the infec=
tion rate. The study determined that the most likely long-term outcome of s=
uch an outbreak would be the extinction of humans. This conclusion stems fr=
om the study's reasoning that the primary epidemiological risk of zombies i=
s the continual growth of the infected population, a phenomenon which would=
 only cease with the infection or death of all surviving humans.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-WhenZombies_25-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-WhenZombies-25"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 2017, a group of students from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/University_of_Leicester" title=3D"University of Leicester">Unive=
rsity of Leicester</a> Department of Physics and Astronomy used an epidemio=
logical model called a SIRS model to plot the spread of a zombie infection.=
 Their findings were presented in the <i>Journal of Physics Special Topics.=
</i> The study concluded that on the 100th day of the epidemic, only 273 hu=
man survivors would remain, outnumbered a million-to-one by the undead. A f=
ollow-up study using different parameters showed that the human population =
could recover.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Government">Government</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZombie_apocalyps=
e&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Government"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_CDC_warning_abo=
ut_zombie_apocalypse" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"2011 CDC warning about=
 zombie apocalypse">2011 CDC warning about zombie apocalypse</a></div>
<p>On May 18, 2011, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centers_fo=
r_Disease_Control_and_Prevention" title=3D"Centers for Disease Control and =
Prevention">Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</a> (CDC) published =
an article, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preparedness_101:_Z=
ombie_Apocalypse" title=3D"Preparedness 101: Zombie Apocalypse">Preparednes=
s 101: Zombie Apocalypse</a></i> providing tips on preparing to survive a z=
ombie invasion.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In a b=
log post, assistant surgeon general <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Ali_S._Khan" title=3D"Ali S. Khan">Ali S. Khan</a> wrote, "That's right, =
I said z-o-m-b-i-e a-p-o-c-a-l-y-p-s-e. You may laugh now, but when it happ=
ens you'll be happy you read this". The post provided instructions for prep=
aring for a zombie onslaught, as a comical way to prepare the public for si=
milar emergencies, such as a hurricane or pandemic. CDC spokesman Dave Daig=
le said that the campaign was a response to a question about whether zombie=
s were a potential danger due to radiation in Japan.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocal=
ypse#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the unclassified document titled "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/CONOP_8888" title=3D"CONOP 8888">CONOP 8888</a>", officers from U=
.S. Strategic Command used a zombie apocalypse scenario as a training templ=
ate for operations, emergencies and catastrophes, as a tool to teach cadets=
 about the basic concepts of military plans and disaster preparation using =
its admittedly outlandish premise.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-29"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Weather">Weather</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZombie_apocalypse&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Weather"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>On October 17, 2011, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Weathe=
r_Channel" title=3D"The Weather Channel">The Weather Channel</a> published =
an article, "How to Weather the Zombie Apocalypse" that included a fictiona=
l interview with a director of research at the CDD, the "Center for Disease=
 Development". The interview involved "Dr. Dale Dixon" answering questions =
about how different weather conditions affect zombies' abilities. Questions=
 included "How does the temperature affect zombies' abilities? Do they run =
faster in warmer temperatures? Do they freeze if it gets too cold?"<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-weather1_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-weather1-31"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Influence_and_legacy">Influ=
ence and legacy</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DZombie_apocalypse&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Influence and legacy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Donald Clarke writing for <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th=
e_Irish_Times" title=3D"The Irish Times">The Irish Times</a></i> described =
<i>Night of the Living Dead</i> as one of the most influential horror films=
 of all time. He commented, "Romero's dark fantasy dragged in many of the a=
nxieties of its age. And, of course, it gave the horror world a new monster=
: a being that rises from the grave to feast on human flesh. They came to b=
e known as zombies".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_7-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-:3-7"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> Jon Towlson of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Fil=
m_Institute" title=3D"British Film Institute">British Film Institute</a> re=
marked that the ground-breaking legacy of the film lies in, "Romero making =
the zombies into flesh-eating beings, creating an allegory of a society dev=
ouring itself from within. This would become the central metaphor underlyin=
g much modern apocalyptic horror".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-32"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> Adam Nayman of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The=
_Ringer_(website)" title=3D"The Ringer (website)">The Ringer</a></i> consid=
ered that the power of the zombie apocalypse movie is its plausibility. He =
said, "<i>In Night of the Living Dead</i> and <i>Dawn of the Dead</i>, Rome=
ro had smartly de-emphasized the <i>why</i> of his zombie outbreaks to focu=
s on the physics (and metaphysics) of human survival: how the end of the wo=
rld would bring out the best and worst in the human condition".<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zo=
mbie_apocalypse#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Nicholas Barber from <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BBC_Culture" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"BB=
C Culture">BBC Culture</a> opined that, "zombies embody the great contempor=
ary fear", noting their "relentless shuffle into the mainstream of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Popular_culture" title=3D"Popular culture=
">popular culture</a>" and particularly highlighted the commercial and crit=
ical success of films like <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/28_D=
ays_Later" title=3D"28 Days Later">28 Days Later</a></i>, <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dawn_of_the_Dead_(2004_film)" title=3D"Dawn of t=
he Dead (2004 film)">Dawn of the Dead</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaun_of_the_Dead" title=3D"Shaun of the Dead">Shaun of =
the Dead</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_9-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-:1-9"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Devon Maloney writing for <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wire=
d_(magazine)" title=3D"Wired (magazine)">Wired</a></i> commented that zombi=
e fandom shares a group mentality that has manifested in group activities l=
ike <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_walk" title=3D"Zombie w=
alk">zombie walks</a>, and that the concept of seeing a zombie as an "other=
" has been a complicated metaphor. He said, "The more realistic apocalypse =
scenarios in movies struggle to be, the more likely people are to consider =
them seriously".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerrang!" title=3D"Kerrang!">Kerrang=
!</a></i>'s Mike Rampton wrote, "Perhaps the most appealing element of a zo=
mbie apocalypse is that it draws people together, forcing them to put their=
 differences aside to unite against a common enemy and set it on fire. Othe=
r than the extraordinary violence involved, that sounds like a dream come t=
rue".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Sophie Collins o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MovieWeb" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"MovieWeb">MovieWeb</a> considered that the appeal of the genre is =
that it is an escapist fantasy about survival: "Perhaps people underestimat=
e what it takes to fight off a swarm of flesh-eating zombies, but almost ev=
eryone thinks they can handle it, and that's exactly what makes these movie=
s so entertaining."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:5_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-:5-3"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> In 2018, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Independent" t=
itle=3D"The Independent">The Independent</a></i> reported the findings of a=
 survey conducted by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Now_(Sky)" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Now (Sky)">NOW TV</a>, which found that almost=
 25% of British people had a plan to survive a zombie apocalypse. The surve=
y also found that one in six had considered putting in place a survival kit=
. Most respondents believed that the zombie apocalypse would begin in <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_City" title=3D"New York City">=
New York City</a> and spread to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lo=
ndon" title=3D"London">London</a>. It also found that one in ten respondent=
s believed that they would only survive for one week in a post-apocalyptic =
world.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_apocalypse#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Genre_examples">Genre examp=
les</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZombie_a=
pocalypse&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Genre =
examples"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Films">Films</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DZombie_apocalypse&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Films"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ul><li><i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Night_of_the_Living_Dea=
d" title=3D"Night of the Living Dead">Night of the Living Dead</a></i> (196=
8), George A. Romero's first film in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Night_of_the_Living_Dead_(film_series)" title=3D"Night of the Living=
 Dead (film series)"><i>Night of the Living Dead</i> film series</a>, spawn=
ed numerous other films in the genre. It follows a group of Pennsylvanians =
